      Which=C2=A020% of a picture of a dog?
   =20
 =20
We  talked yesterday about some people who bought an online pointer to a di=
gital picture of a dog (a non-fungible token,=C2=A0or NFT)=C2=A0for $4 mill=
ion and, a few months later, =E2=80=9Cfractionalized=E2=80=9D it into 16,96=
9,696,969=C2=A0tokens[1] and sold 20% of them for $45 million, giving the p=
icture of a dog a total market value of about $225 million. (It doubled the=
 next day, though it later came down a bit.) I do feel like, when I started=
 in the financial industry in 2007, this would have been easily=C2=A0the cr=
aziest and most important financial story of the year, and now it is just=
=C2=A0Thursday in NFTs.Anyway I made some jokes and expressed some exaspera=
tion about this yesterday, and then I got a brilliant email from a reader, =
who wrote:I wonder which 20% of the picture of the dog was sold. If you sli=
ce a picture into 17 billion pieces, by definition they cannot all be the s=
ame. It seems plausible that the original buyers identified the most valuab=
le part of the picture, which was all along valued at $229mm, and sold that=
 (presumably the face/head). The remaining 80% of the picture would be wort=
h negative $225mm (from the collective emotional trauma / revulsion / thera=
py costs of all beholders of a picture of a decapitated shiba inu). Obvious=
ly each part of the face would have different values, so this is only a pro=
xy. With no mark-to-market for the body and background, we=E2=80=99ll never=
 know for sure.Now, to be clear, this is not what actually happened here. T=
he picture of the dog was not sliced into 17 billion distinct pieces, each =
with its own color and location on the picture. You couldn=E2=80=99t pay mo=
re to get the tip of the nose and less to get some random pixel in the back=
ground. =E2=80=9COwnership=E2=80=9D of the picture of the dog =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0in the asterisked NFT sense; you don=E2=80=99t really own it in a tradit=
ional way =E2=80=94=C2=A0was sliced into 16,969,696,969=C2=A0shares. Each d=
og-picture token is identical to the 16,969,696,968=C2=A0others,=C2=A0and t=
hey trade in a liquid=C2=A0market at a market price. Buying a token doesn=
=E2=80=99t get you one particular pixel of the dog picture; it gets you one=
 (1/16,969,696,969)=C2=A0share=C2=A0of the whole picture. Like buying one s=
hare of Apple Inc. stock doesn=E2=80=99t entitle you to a particular iPhone=
 in Apple=E2=80=99s inventory, but to fractional (1/16,530,166,000) ownersh=
ip (in another asterisked sense) of=C2=A0all=C2=A0of Apple=E2=80=99s invent=
ory and intellectual property and future cash flows and so forth.=C2=A0In o=
ther words the dog-picture tokens are=C2=A0fungible=C2=A0tokens representin=
g fractional ownership of a non-fungible token (the dog picture).In one sen=
se, of course, that=E2=80=99s the only way this could work. What you need, =
to get the price of a picture of a dog to ridiculous levels, is a fungible =
market. You want there to be a lot of tokens that all have the same market =
price, that people can trade back and forth with each other and create a fr=
enzy. If the dog picture is sliced into=C2=A017 billion tokens and I sell y=
ou 100 of them for $1, then guess what, the dog picture=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9C=
value=E2=80=9D is $170 million.[2] Slicing a thing into billions of tokens =
and then trading a few of them for a small amount of money is a good way to=
 create the impression that the thing is very valuable, and that impression=
 can take on a life of its own: If people see a $170 million picture of a d=
og they might want to buy some of that. (In fact, at the peak last week, th=
e picture-of-a-dog tokens were trading tens of millions of dollars=E2=80=99=
 worth per day; this is not, like  the New Jersey deli, a case of an inflat=
ed market value based on thin trading. But the principle still applies: You=
 don=E2=80=99t need anyone to be buying $10 million chunks of the dog token=
 to get a $225 million valuation; you just need lots of people to be tradin=
g $1 or $10 or $100 chunks.)But in another sense my reader=E2=80=99s email =
points to really a much better and funnier way to do this? If you are going=
 to buy an NFT and carve it up and sell fractions of it, as sort of a finan=
cial experiment and funny art project, really you should sell non-fungible =
shares, no? =E2=80=9CBuy=E2=80=9D a picture of a dog and then =E2=80=9Csell=
=E2=80=9D each pixel of the picture, or =E2=80=9Csell=E2=80=9D each byte of=
 the smart contract entitling you to the picture of the dog, or whatever. T=
he lesson of the NFT boom is that you=C2=A0can=C2=A0create a market like th=
at, that you don=E2=80=99t always need fungibility to get liquidity, that p=
eople actually want to buy =E2=80=9Cunique=E2=80=9D but almost-identical di=
gital objects and will pay more for vanishingly small gradations in status.=
 A pixel in the background of the dog picture might be worth a fraction of =
a penny; the tip of the nose might be worth millions, might be worth more t=
han the picture of the dog itself, I don=E2=80=99t know.Another reader emai=
led me yesterday to say =E2=80=9CI am as amused/perplexed by the whole NFT =
situation as it seems you are, but on one level it is such a great way for =
the market to reward humor.=E2=80=9D I don=E2=80=99t exactly disagree with =
that. I think that some of what is going on with the NFT boom is a complex =
and emergent form of=C2=A0financial manipulation, a way for people in the c=
rypto ecosystem to (consciously or not) pump up=C2=A0the value of that ecos=
ystem by trading weird stuff at high nominal values. But another thing that=
 is definitely going on with the NFT boom is that people keep finding funny=
 things to =E2=80=9Csell=E2=80=9D online, and other people respond to the j=
okes with money, because they enjoy them. Seems good! It gives crypto inves=
tors the chance to enjoy conceptual art and have a good laugh; who am I to =
complain.=C2=A0But I do think that the jokes could be better! The first per=
son to burn a painting and sell an NFT =E2=80=9Cof=E2=80=9D the burnt paint=
ing was a little funny, sure, derivative of pre-NFT artists but still funny=
. But by the hundredth =E2=80=9Cobject-fire-token-money=E2=80=9D NFT, just,=
 come on man, be a little creative! I  have argued that at this point it wo=
uld be funnier and more interesting to sell an NFT on a painting,=C2=A0keep=
=C2=A0the painting, and then sell the actual painting to someone else. Who =
owns the =E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D painting then? What=C2=A0is=C2=A0the NFT, i=
n that scenario? Etc. Burning the painting is boring now.Similarly here, lo=
ok, it is funny to sell fungible fractional ownership of a non-fungible tok=
en=C2=A0of a picture of a dog for tens of millions of dollars, I am not goi=
ng to deny that, I have spent a lot of time, here in this column, laughing =
about it. But selling=C2=A0non-fungible=C2=A0fractional ownership of a=C2=
=A0non-fungible token of a picture of a dog =E2=80=94=C2=A0an NFT-squared, =
if you will =E2=80=94=C2=A0for tens of millions of dollars?=C2=A0That=E2=80=
=99s=C2=A0funny.
