      Due diligence
   =20
 =20
Here is a post from Aug. 15 on Reddit=E2=80=99s WallStreetBets message boar=
d. It begins:Hello. On August 12th, something very strange happened. The ur=
l amazon.com/affirm no longer led to an error message. In fact, it redirect=
s to a link that says "Pay over time with Affirm" in the tab title, and, if=
 you're on the app it says "Search in Pay over time with Affirm" in the sea=
rch bar.=C2=A0It goes on from there, but that=E2=80=99s the essential obser=
vation: A page on Amazon.com Inc.=E2=80=99s=C2=A0website had changed, on Au=
g. 12, to suggest that Amazon had entered into a=C2=A0partnership with Affi=
rm Holdings Inc., a buy-now-pay-later provider. And in fact Amazon did anno=
unce a partnership with Affirm, in which customers can use Affirm to pay fo=
r Amazon purchases. This partnership seems good for Affirm=E2=80=99s busine=
ss =E2=80=94=C2=A0Amazon is giant and sells lots of stuff =E2=80=94=C2=A0an=
d its stock was up 47% the trading day after the partnership was announced.=
But the partnership was announced on Aug. 27. Amazon updated its website tw=
o weeks earlier, presumably during negotiations for the partnership. Not in=
 a particularly user-facing way; I don=E2=80=99t think you could have gotte=
n to amazon.com/affirm by clicking on anything obvious on the Amazon homepa=
ge. But in the basement of Amazon=E2=80=99s website, people were doing stuf=
f to prepare for a partnership with Affirm, and some of that basement was e=
xposed on the web, and if you were looking for it =E2=80=94=C2=A0if, say, y=
ou had a list of companies you thought Amazon might partner with, and you=
=C2=A0went to your browser every day and spent two minutes typing =E2=80=9C=
amazon.com/company-name=E2=80=9D into the address bar for each of those pot=
ential partners =E2=80=94=C2=A0you would have found something.The Reddit us=
er who posted that also said he owned a bunch of Affirm call options; presu=
mably he=C2=A0made a ton of money on the announcement.I wanted to mention t=
his for two reasons. One is that it is popular to think =E2=80=94=C2=A0and =
certainly I imply it a lot around here =E2=80=94=C2=A0that Reddit, and part=
icularly WallStreetBets, is a place for people who want to YOLO call option=
s on GameStop for purely social and comedic reasons, that the main function=
 of the site is to egg people on as they buy a few meme stocks at increasin=
gly unhinged valuations. But actually a major=C2=A0function of the site is =
sharing fundamental due diligence =E2=80=94=C2=A0or whatever this is =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0on non-meme stocks. (And meme stocks, too, to be fair; you can rea=
d fundamental analyses of GameStop Corp. if you want.) And while much (sure=
ly not all) of this due diligence is =E2=80=9Camateur,=E2=80=9D in the stri=
ct sense that it is written by people who do not have day jobs in the inves=
ting industry, some of that amateur due diligence is pretty good. If you re=
ad this post you could have made some real money!The other reason is, you k=
now, insider trading? Did these people trade on material nonpublic informat=
ion? Is information on a public web page, but a public web page that the co=
mpany didn=E2=80=99t mean for you to see, =E2=80=9Cnonpublic=E2=80=9D? I du=
nno;=C2=A0I think there=E2=80=99s an argument that it is? (If Amazon made t=
his change to one web page, and then=C2=A0Amazon executives=C2=A0bought up =
Affirm call options, they would be charged with insider trading and couldn=
=E2=80=99t get away with saying =E2=80=9Cno no no this news was public, see=
, we modified one web page.=E2=80=9D) But even if this is nonpublic, that=
=E2=80=99s not enough: In U.S. insider trading law it is not necessarily il=
legal to trade on material nonpublic information; it=E2=80=99s only illegal=
 to trade on material nonpublic information that you got in a bad way.Usual=
ly this means that you got it in breach of some duty of confidentiality or =
relationship of trust and confidence, which is hard to imagine here. (Just =
some random guy on Reddit looking at Amazon=E2=80=99s website.) But it is m=
ore or less  settled law in the U.S. that it is=C2=A0also illegal to trade =
on material nonpublic information that you obtain by hacking into a company=
=E2=80=99s computer systems. I think that if you are reading this column, i=
t is likely that you just said to yourself =E2=80=9Ccome on, typing a word =
in the address bar is not =E2=80=98hacking,=E2=80=99 where is this guy even=
 going with this?=E2=80=9D But I am sorry to say that U.S. prosecutors and =
judges do not always think like that. There is a lively debate in the law a=
bout whether automated scraping of public websites can constitute=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9Chacking,=E2=80=9D and people have been charged with criminal hacking =
for guessing interesting URLs.=C2=A0The line between =E2=80=9Cguessing what=
 URLs have interesting stuff in them and typing them in you browser=E2=80=
=99s address bar=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cguessing passwords to hack into a ne=
twork=E2=80=9D might not be super-clear in the law.=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t th=
ink this is insider trading under U.S. law; I think this is fine and cool. =
(Not legal advice!) But when people say things like =E2=80=9Ccheating and i=
nsider trading are bad and should be illegal, but good careful research is =
fine and should be rewarded,=E2=80=9D it is sometimes hard to know what the=
y mean. This feels to me like good careful research but I suspect others wo=
uld see it as cheating.
