      ESG: Greenium
   =20
 =20
We have talked a  couple of  times this week=C2=A0about ESG loans, bank loa=
ns where companies pay a bit less interest for hitting certain environmenta=
l, social and governance targets but pay a bit more interest if they miss t=
hose targets. One fact about these loans is that the discounts and penaltie=
s tend to be small, often one or five basis points either way.A different b=
ut related form of ESG borrowing is a =E2=80=9Cgreen bond.=E2=80=9D In a gr=
een bond, a company borrows money and commits to use it for some sort of en=
vironmental-sustainability project; in exchange, the bond carries an intere=
st rate that is lower than the company would ordinarily pay. (ESG loans, on=
 the other hand, usually have no committed use of proceeds, but have higher=
 or lower interest depending on whether the company does enough green thing=
s.) This difference =E2=80=94=C2=A0the reduction in the interest rate for d=
oing green stuff =E2=80=94=C2=A0is called the =E2=80=9Cgreenium.=E2=80=9D W=
ith demand for environmental sustainability soaring, the greenium=C2=A0is h=
igher now than it has ever been.=C2=A0Also it is two basis points:There has=
 never been a better time to sell green bonds in Europe.=C2=A0A boom in ESG=
 investing has pushed up the =E2=80=9Cgreenium=E2=80=9D investors are willi=
ng to pay for debt that complies with a set of environmental, social, and g=
overnance criteria, according to Deutsche Bank AG. That=E2=80=99s flushed o=
ut debut green deals from issuers as diverse as Spain and Oreo-cookie maker=
 Mondelez International Inc.=E2=80=9CWe are now able to go to issuers and t=
ell them =E2=80=98if you issue your debt in green format, you will actually=
 save money,=E2=80=99 meaning that the hurdles we had to overcome for our c=
lients to issue green bonds are now gone,=E2=80=9D said Henrik Johnsson, co=
-head of investment banking EMEA at Deutsche Bank in London. =E2=80=9CWe ar=
e in a Goldilocks moment.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9CEverything else equal,=
 investors are willing to pay more for a green bond than for a conventional=
 bond,=E2=80=9D Pablo de Ramon-Laca, director general of Spain=E2=80=99s Tr=
easury said in an interview with Bloomberg TV Wednesday. The government cit=
ed an estimate by lead managers on the deal that it achieved a greenium =E2=
=80=9Cof around 2 basis points.=E2=80=9DTo be fair, the greenium is sometim=
es bigger for corporate borrowers, particularly ones that pay higher rates =
generally. Except that 39% of the time it apparently isn=E2=80=99t?Accordin=
g to Deutsche Bank research, borrowers of green bonds got a reduced rate vi=
s-a-vis their outstanding debt on 61% of deals sold in the second half of 2=
020, an increase over the first half.There are  two great narratives of ESG=
 investing: =E2=80=9CWe will invest in good-ESG companies rather than bad-E=
SG companies in order to raise the cost of capital for bad-ESG companies an=
d drive bad ESG practices out of the market, accepting a lower return on in=
vestment for ourselves in order to create incentives for companies to do th=
e right thing,=E2=80=9D versus =E2=80=9Cwe will invest in good-ESG companie=
s because they will outperform in a future world that cares more about envi=
ronmental and social issues, so we will get a higher return on investment f=
or ourselves.=E2=80=9D People kind of hate that first narrative because it=
=C2=A0requires them to accept lower returns, and nobody wants that; everyon=
e would rather say =E2=80=9Cwe do well while doing good=E2=80=9D instead of=
 =E2=80=9Cwe do good by sacrificing some money.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0The greenium,=
 of course, fits with the first narrative: Investors explicitly accept a lo=
wer return on investment[3] in exchange for financing good ESG projects and=
 not bad ones. They are willing to pay =E2=80=94=C2=A0accept a lower intere=
st rate =E2=80=94=C2=A0for something that makes them feel good. They=E2=80=
=99re just not willing to pay very much.
