      ESG: Recycling
   =20
 =20
I have been saying for the last  couple of  days that =E2=80=9Cthere is pro=
bably a lot of value to be created by telling people soothing things about =
ESG, and in practice, if someone creates=C2=A0that value, a lot of intermed=
iaries in the chain will capture some of it.=E2=80=9D People want to think =
that their investing dollars go to companies that are doing good things on =
environmental, social and governance metrics, but they don=E2=80=99t want t=
o think=C2=A0too much=C2=A0about it. If you start a mutual fund with the wo=
rd =E2=80=9CSustainable=E2=80=9D in the name (or rename an existing mutual =
fund with =E2=80=9CSustainable=E2=80=9D), people will buy it, and even if y=
ou just invest in a broad market index, your investors will be=C2=A0happier=
=C2=A0than if you called it an index fund. In a sense you are doing fraud, =
sure sure sure, but in another sense you are creating real value from nothi=
ng and appropriating some of it for yourself. But in most senses you are do=
ing fraud.Anyway this is kind of amazing:The triangular =E2=80=9Cchasing ar=
rows=E2=80=9D recycling symbol is everywhere: On disposable cups. On shower=
 curtains. On children=E2=80=99s toys.What a lot of shoppers might not know=
 is that any product can display the sign, even if it isn=E2=80=99t recycla=
ble. It=E2=80=99s false advertising, critics say, and as a result, countles=
s tons of non-recyclable garbage are thrown in the recycling bin each year,=
 choking the recycling system.Late on Wednesday, California took steps towa=
rd becoming the first state to change that. A bill passed by the state=E2=
=80=99s assembly would ban companies from using the arrows symbol unless th=
ey can prove the material is in fact recycled in most California communitie=
s, and is used to make new products. =E2=80=A6The recycling symbol is =E2=
=80=9Csubconsciously telling the people buying things, =E2=80=98You=E2=80=
=99re environmentally friendly,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D said Heidi Sanborn, the e=
xecutive director of the National Stewardship Action Council, which advocat=
es corporations to shoulder more responsibility for recycling their product=
s.=E2=80=9CNobody should be able to lie to the public,=E2=80=9D she said.We=
ll but what if the public wants to be lied to? What if the main thing peopl=
e want is precisely to be told =E2=80=9Cyou=E2=80=99re environmentally frie=
ndly=E2=80=9D? =E2=80=9CThe plastics and packaging industry has opposed the=
 bill, saying it would create more confusion for consumers, not less.=E2=80=
=9D
