      People are worried about stock buybacks
   =20
 =20
Sure  why not:Two senior Democratic senators proposed a 2% tax on corporate=
 stock buybacks in an effort to boost investment and reduce what they terme=
d as tax avoidance.The plan, released by Senate Finance Committee Chairman =
Ron Wyden of Oregon and Senate Banking Committee Chairman Sherrod Brown of =
Ohio, comes as Democratic lawmakers assemble a raft of tax measures to help=
 pay for a $3.5 trillion budget bill that contains the bulk of President Jo=
e Biden=E2=80=99s longer-term economic agenda.=E2=80=9CRather than investin=
g in their workers, mega-corporations used the windfall from Republicans=E2=
=80=99 2017 tax cuts to juice their stock prices and reward their wealthies=
t investors and their executives through massive stock buybacks,=E2=80=9D W=
yden said in a statement on the proposal Friday.The 2% excise tax on stock =
buybacks pitched by Wyden and Brown wouldn=E2=80=99t apply to transactions =
for funding an employee pension plan or those below a =E2=80=9Cde minimis t=
hreshold,=E2=80=9D according to a statement released by Brown=E2=80=99s off=
ice. =E2=80=9CSpecial rules address the treatment of foreign corporations,=
=E2=80=9D though so-called inverted companies -- a term used to describe Am=
erican firms that shift their headquarters abroad -- =E2=80=9Care fully sub=
ject to the excise tax.=E2=80=9DI tend to think of stock buybacks and divid=
ends as more or less identical transactions, but one important difference b=
etween them is that buybacks are more tax-efficient. If a company pays a di=
vidend, every shareholder gets cash and has to pay taxes on it. If a compan=
y buys back stock, shareholders who don=E2=80=99t sell pay no taxes (but be=
nefit because their=C2=A0ownership interest in the company is increased); s=
hareholders who do sell pay taxes, but even they don=E2=80=99t pay taxes on=
 the full amount of cash received (just their gain over what they paid for =
the stock). If you don=E2=80=99t like buybacks because they are used by com=
panies to =E2=80=9Creward their wealthiest investors=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Crath=
er than investing in their workers,=E2=80=9D then dividends are really just=
 as bad. But if you don=E2=80=99t like buybacks because they do that=C2=A0a=
nd are tax-efficient=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0if, for instance, you are a senato=
r looking to raise government revenue =E2=80=94=C2=A0then, sure, slap an ex=
cise tax on them.
