<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;"><em>Which=C2=A0</em>20% of a picture of a dog?</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/25008175.273683/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDktMDkvdHdlbnR5LXBlcmNlbnQtb2YtYS1waWN0dXJlLW9m=
LWEtZG9n/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa61e1c44" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked yesterday</a> about some people w=
ho bought an online pointer to a digital picture of a dog (a non-fungible t=
oken,=C2=A0or NFT)=C2=A0for $4 million and, a few months later, =E2=80=9Cfr=
actionalized=E2=80=9D it into 16,969,696,969=C2=A0tokens[1] and sold 20% of=
 them for $45 million, giving the picture of a dog a total market value of =
about $225 million. (It doubled the next day, though it later came down a b=
it.) I do feel like, when I started in the financial industry in 2007, this=
 would have been easily=C2=A0the craziest and most important financial stor=
y of the year, and now it is just=C2=A0Thursday in NFTs.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">Anyway I made some jokes and expressed some exasperation abou=
t this yesterday, and then I got a brilliant email from a reader, who wrote=
:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I wonder <em>which</em> 20% o=
f the picture of the dog was sold. If you slice a picture into 17 billion p=
ieces, by definition they cannot all be the same. It seems plausible that t=
he original buyers identified the most valuable part of the picture, which =
was all along valued at $229mm, and sold that (presumably the face/head). T=
he remaining 80% of the picture would be worth negative $225mm (from the co=
llective emotional trauma / revulsion / therapy costs of all beholders of a=
 picture of a decapitated shiba inu). Obviously each part of the face would=
 have different values, so this is only a proxy. With no mark-to-market for=
 the body and background, we=E2=80=99ll never know for sure.</p></blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, to be clear, this is not what actually =
happened here. The picture of the dog was not sliced into 17 billion distin=
ct pieces, each with its own color and location on the picture. You couldn=
=E2=80=99t pay more to get the tip of the nose and less to get some random =
pixel in the background. =E2=80=9COwnership=E2=80=9D of the picture of the =
dog =E2=80=94=C2=A0in the asterisked NFT sense; you don=E2=80=99t really ow=
n it in a traditional way =E2=80=94=C2=A0was sliced into 16,969,696,969=C2=
=A0shares. Each dog-picture token is identical to the 16,969,696,968=C2=A0o=
thers,=C2=A0and they trade in a liquid=C2=A0market at a market price. Buyin=
g a token doesn=E2=80=99t get you one particular pixel of the dog picture; =
it gets you one (1/16,969,696,969)=C2=A0<em>share=C2=A0</em>of the whole pi=
cture. Like buying one share of Apple Inc. stock doesn=E2=80=99t entitle yo=
u to a particular iPhone in Apple=E2=80=99s inventory, but to fractional (1=
/<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25008175.273683/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMzIwMTkzLzAw=
MDAzMjAxOTMyMTAwMDA2NS9hYXBsLTIwMjEwNjI2Lmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe57=
ca662" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">16,=
530,166,000</a>) ownership (in another asterisked sense) of=C2=A0<em>all=C2=
=A0</em>of Apple=E2=80=99s inventory and intellectual property and future c=
ash flows and so forth.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In other word=
s the dog-picture tokens are=C2=A0<em>fungible=C2=A0</em>tokens representin=
g fractional ownership of a non-fungible token (the dog picture).</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In one sense, of course, that=E2=80=99s the only way=
 this could work. What you need, to get the price of a picture of a dog to =
ridiculous levels, is a fungible market. You want there to be a lot of toke=
ns that all have the same market price, that people can trade back and fort=
h with each other and create a frenzy. If the dog picture is sliced into=C2=
=A017 billion tokens and I sell you 100 of them for $1, then guess what, th=
e dog picture=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cvalue=E2=80=9D is $170 million.[2] Slicing=
 a thing into billions of tokens and then trading a few of them for a small=
 amount of money is a good way to create the impression that the thing is v=
ery valuable, and that impression can take on a life of its own: If people =
see a $170 million picture of a dog they might want to buy some of that. (I=
n fact, at the peak last week, the picture-of-a-dog tokens were trading ten=
s of millions of dollars=E2=80=99 worth per day; this is not, like <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25008175.273683/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMjAvaG9tZXRvd24t=
aW50ZXJuYXRpb25hbC1uZXctamVyc2V5LWRlbGktaXMtYWN0dWFsbHktd29ydGgtMi1iaWxsaW9=
u/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3213f06c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;"> the New Jersey deli</a>, a case of an inflated =
market value based on thin trading. But the principle still applies: You do=
n=E2=80=99t need anyone to be buying $10 million chunks of the dog token to=
 get a $225 million valuation; you just need lots of people to be trading $=
1 or $10 or $100 chunks.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in another se=
nse my reader=E2=80=99s email points to really a much better and funnier wa=
y to do this? If you are going to buy an NFT and carve it up and sell fract=
ions of it, as sort of a financial experiment and funny art project, really=
 you should sell non-fungible shares, no? =E2=80=9CBuy=E2=80=9D a picture o=
f a dog and then =E2=80=9Csell=E2=80=9D each pixel of the picture, or =E2=
=80=9Csell=E2=80=9D each byte of the smart contract entitling you to the pi=
cture of the dog, or whatever. The lesson of the NFT boom is that you=C2=A0=
<em>can=C2=A0</em>create a market like that, that you don=E2=80=99t always =
need fungibility to get liquidity, that people actually <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25008175.273683/aHR0cHM6Ly90ZWNoY3J1b=
mNoLmNvbS8yMDIxLzA5LzAzL2xvb3QtZ2FtZXMtdGhlLWNyeXB0by13b3JsZC8/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB88de1e93" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">want</a> to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/25008175.273683/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2hyaXN0aWVzLmNvbS9mZWF0dXJlcy8xMC10=
aGluZ3MtdG8ta25vdy1hYm91dC1DcnlwdG9QdW5rcy0xMTU2OS0xLmFzcHg/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cB8ac2ac8c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;">buy</a> =E2=80=9Cunique=E2=80=9D but <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25008175.273683/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY25iYy5jb20vMj=
AyMS8wOC8yMy9wZW9wbGUtYXJlLXBheWluZy1taWxsaW9ucy1vZi1kb2xsYXJzLWZvci1kaWdpd=
GFsLXBpY3R1cmVzLW9mLXJvY2tzLmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbc1a1685" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">almost-identica=
l</a> digital objects and will pay more for vanishingly small gradations in=
 status. A pixel in the background of the dog picture might be worth a frac=
tion of a penny; the tip of the nose might be worth millions, might be wort=
h more than the picture of the dog itself, I don=E2=80=99t know.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another reader emailed me yesterday to say =E2=80=9CI=
 am as amused/perplexed by the whole NFT situation as it seems you are, but=
 on one level it is such a great way for the market to reward humor.=E2=80=
=9D I don=E2=80=99t exactly disagree with that. I think that some of what i=
s going on with the NFT boom is a complex and emergent form of=C2=A0financi=
al manipulation, a way for people in the crypto ecosystem to (consciously o=
r not) pump up=C2=A0the value of that ecosystem by trading weird stuff at h=
igh nominal values. But another thing that is definitely going on with the =
NFT boom is that people keep finding funny things to =E2=80=9Csell=E2=80=9D=
 online, and other people respond to the jokes with money, because they enj=
oy them. Seems good! It gives crypto investors the chance to enjoy conceptu=
al art and have a good laugh; who am I to complain.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">But I do think that the jokes could be better! The first per=
son to burn a painting and sell an NFT =E2=80=9Cof=E2=80=9D the burnt paint=
ing was a little funny, sure, derivative of pre-NFT artists but still funny=
. But by the hundredth =E2=80=9Cobject-fire-token-money=E2=80=9D NFT, just,=
 come on man, be a little creative! I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/25008175.273683/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGl=
uaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDUtMjQvbWVycmlsbC1seW5jaC1wdXRzLWRvd24tdGhlLXBob2=
5l/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB73c2ee02" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border=
-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: soli=
d; background-color: #ccc;"> have argued</a> that at this point it would be=
 funnier and more interesting to sell an NFT on a painting,=C2=A0<em>keep=
=C2=A0</em>the painting, and then sell the actual painting to someone else.=
 Who owns the =E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D painting then? What=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0<=
/em>the NFT, in that scenario? Etc. Burning the painting is boring now.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Similarly here, look, it is funny to sell fung=
ible fractional ownership of a non-fungible token=C2=A0of a picture of a do=
g for tens of millions of dollars, I am not going to deny that, I have spen=
t a lot of time, here in this column, laughing about it. But selling=C2=A0<=
em>non-fungible=C2=A0</em>fractional ownership of a=C2=A0non-fungible token=
 of a picture of a dog =E2=80=94=C2=A0an NFT-squared, if you will =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0for tens of millions of dollars?=C2=A0<em>That=E2=80=99s=C2=A0</em>fu=
nny.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsored-content" width=3D"auto" cellpa=
dding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0">
