<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Due diligence</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/25008175.273683/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucmVkZGl0LmNvbS9y=
L3dhbGxzdHJlZXRiZXRzL2NvbW1lbnRzL3A1MG41cC9hbXpuX2lzX3VwX3RvX3NvbWV0aGluZ19=
3aXRoX2Fmcm1fb2JzZXNzaXZlX2RkLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB12df4394" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a post</a> from Au=
g. 15 on Reddit=E2=80=99s WallStreetBets message board. It begins:</p><bloc=
kquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hello. On August 12th, something very s=
trange happened. The url amazon.com/affirm no longer led to an error messag=
e. In fact, it redirects to a link that says "Pay over time with Affirm" in=
 the tab title, and, if you're on the app it says "Search in Pay over time =
with Affirm" in the search bar.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">It goes on from there, but that=E2=80=99s the essential observation=
: A page on Amazon.com Inc.=E2=80=99s=C2=A0website had changed, on Aug. 12,=
 to suggest that Amazon had entered into a=C2=A0partnership with Affirm Hol=
dings Inc., a buy-now-pay-later provider. And in fact Amazon did announce a=
 partnership with Affirm, in which customers can use Affirm to pay for Amaz=
on purchases. This partnership seems good for Affirm=E2=80=99s business =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0Amazon is giant and sells lots of stuff =E2=80=94=C2=A0and its =
stock was up 47% the trading day after the partnership was announced.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the partnership <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25008175.273683/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9Bcm=
NoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4MjA5NTMvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIxMTEwNjk3L3RtMjEyNjQyM2QxX=
2V4OTktMS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc82d011b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">was announced on Aug. 27</a>. Amazo=
n updated its website two weeks earlier, presumably during negotiations for=
 the partnership. Not in a particularly user-facing way; I don=E2=80=99t th=
ink you could have gotten to amazon.com/affirm by clicking on anything obvi=
ous on the Amazon homepage. But in the basement of Amazon=E2=80=99s website=
, people were doing stuff to prepare for a partnership with Affirm, and som=
e of that basement was exposed on the web, and if you were looking for it =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0if, say, you had a list of companies you thought Amazon migh=
t partner with, and you=C2=A0went to your browser every day and spent two m=
inutes typing =E2=80=9Camazon.com/company-name=E2=80=9D into the address ba=
r for each of those potential partners =E2=80=94=C2=A0you would have found =
something.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Reddit user who posted that =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25008175.273683/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cucmVkZGl0LmNvbS9yL3dhbGxzdHJlZXRiZXRzL2NvbW1lbnRzL3A1MG41cC9hb=
XpuX2lzX3VwX3RvX3NvbWV0aGluZ193aXRoX2Fmcm1fb2JzZXNzaXZlX2RkL2hhbWs5c3AvP3V0=
bV9zb3VyY2U9cmVkZGl0JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09d2ViMngmY29udGV4dD0z/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB32e77512" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;">also said</a> he owned a bunch of Affirm call options; presumably he=
=C2=A0made a ton of money on the announcement.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">I wanted to mention this for two reasons. One is that it is popular to =
think =E2=80=94=C2=A0and certainly I imply it a lot around here =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0that Reddit, and particularly WallStreetBets, is a place for people w=
ho want to YOLO call options on GameStop for purely social and comedic reas=
ons, that the main function of the site is to egg people on as they buy a f=
ew meme stocks at increasingly unhinged valuations. But actually a major=C2=
=A0function of the site is sharing fundamental due diligence =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0or whatever this is =E2=80=94=C2=A0on non-meme stocks. (And meme stocks,=
 too, to be fair; you can read fundamental analyses of GameStop Corp. if yo=
u want.) And while much (surely not all) of this due diligence is =E2=80=9C=
amateur,=E2=80=9D in the strict sense that it is written by people who do n=
ot have day jobs in the investing industry, some of that amateur due dilige=
nce is pretty good. If you read this post you could have made some real mon=
ey!</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other reason is, you know, insider =
trading? Did these people trade on material nonpublic information? Is infor=
mation on a public web page, but a public web page that the company didn=E2=
=80=99t mean for you to see, =E2=80=9Cnonpublic=E2=80=9D? I dunno;=C2=A0I t=
hink there=E2=80=99s an argument that it is? (If Amazon made this change to=
 one web page, and then=C2=A0<em>Amazon executives=C2=A0</em>bought up Affi=
rm call options, they would be charged with insider trading and couldn=E2=
=80=99t get away with saying =E2=80=9Cno no no this news was public, see, w=
e modified one web page.=E2=80=9D) But even if this is nonpublic, that=E2=
=80=99s not enough: In U.S. insider trading law it is not necessarily illeg=
al to trade on material nonpublic information; it=E2=80=99s only illegal to=
 trade on material nonpublic information that you got in a bad way.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Usually this means that you got it in breach of so=
me duty of confidentiality or relationship of trust and confidence, which i=
s hard to imagine here. (Just some random guy on Reddit looking at Amazon=
=E2=80=99s website.) But it is more or less <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/25008175.273683/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTUtMDgtMTEvd2h5LW5vdC1pbnNpZGVyLXRyYWRlLW9uLWV2=
ZXJ5LWNvbXBhbnkt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa8270f55" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> settled law</a> in the U.S. that=
 it is=C2=A0also illegal to trade on material nonpublic information that yo=
u obtain by hacking into a company=E2=80=99s computer systems. I think that=
 if you are reading this column, it is likely that you just said to yoursel=
f =E2=80=9Ccome on, typing a word in the address bar is not =E2=80=98hackin=
g,=E2=80=99 where is this guy even going with this?=E2=80=9D But I am sorry=
 to say that U.S. prosecutors and judges do not always think like that. The=
re is a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25008175.2=
73683/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubml4b25wZWFib2R5LmNvbS9lbi9pZGVhcy9ibG9nL2RhdGEtcHJpd=
mFjeS8yMDIxLzA2LzI4L3dlYi1zY3JhcGluZy1iYXR0bGUtdG8tcHJvdmlkZS1mdXJ0aGVyLWNs=
YXJpZmljYXRpb24tdG8tY29tcHV0ZXItZnJhdWQtYW5kLWFidXNlLWFjdC1jZmFh/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB01fbe1e8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">lively debate</a> in the law about whether automated scrapin=
g of public websites can constitute=C2=A0=E2=80=9Chacking,=E2=80=9D and peo=
ple have been <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2500=
8175.273683/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZWZmLm9yZy9kZWVwbGlua3MvMjAxMy8wNy93ZWV2cy1jYXN=
lLWZsYXdlZC1iZWdpbm5pbmctZW5k/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0185fd44" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">charged with crimi=
nal hacking</a> for guessing interesting URLs.=C2=A0The line between =E2=80=
=9Cguessing what URLs have interesting stuff in them and typing them in you=
 browser=E2=80=99s address bar=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cguessing passwords to =
hack into a network=E2=80=9D might not be super-clear in the law.=C2=A0</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t think this is insider trading =
under U.S. law; I think this is fine and cool. (Not legal advice!) But when=
 people say things like =E2=80=9Ccheating and insider trading are bad and s=
hould be illegal, but good careful research is fine and should be rewarded,=
=E2=80=9D it is sometimes hard to know what they mean. This feels to me lik=
e good careful research but I suspect others would see it as cheating.</p><=
